data.name: Bitcoin
data.description: The world’s first cryptocurrency, Bitcoin is stored and exchanged securely on the internet through a digital ledger known as a blockchain. Bitcoins are divisible into smaller units known as satoshis — each satoshi is worth 0.00000001 bitcoin.

data.name: Ethereum
data.description: Ethereum is both a cryptocurrency and a decentralized computing platform. Developers can use the platform to create decentralized applications and issue new crypto assets, known as Ethereum tokens.

data.name: XRP
data.description: XRP is the cryptocurrency used by the Ripple payment network. Built for enterprise use, XRP aims to be a fast, cost-efficient cryptocurrency for cross-border payments.

data.name: Bitcoin Cash
data.description: Bitcoin Cash is a fork of Bitcoin that seeks to add more transaction capacity to the network in order to be useful for everyday transactions.

data.name: Litecoin
data.description: Litecoin is a cryptocurrency that uses a faster payment confirmation schedule and a different cryptographic algorithm than Bitcoin.

data.name: EOS
data.description: EOS is a cryptocurrency designed to support large-scale applications. There are no fees to send or receive EOS. Instead, the protocol rewards the entities that run the network periodically with new EOS, effectively substituting inflation for transaction fees.

data.name: Bitcoin SV
data.description: Bitcoin SV is a fork of Bitcoin Cash (BCH). It attempts to restore the original Bitcoin protocol as defined by version 0.1 of Bitcoin.

data.name: Stellar Lumens
data.description: Stellar’s cryptocurrency, the Stellar Lumen (XLM), powers the Stellar payment network. Stellar aims to connect banks, payment systems, and individuals quickly and reliably.

data.name: Chainlink
data.description: Chainlink (LINK) is an Ethereum token that powers the Chainlink decentralized oracle network. This network allows smart contracts on Ethereum to securely connect to external data sources, APIs, and payment systems.

data.name: Dash
data.description: Dash is a cryptocurrency with optional speed and privacy features. Its unique network architecture consists of both regular miners and privileged machines called Masternodes.

data.name: Tezos
data.description: Tezos is a cryptocurrency and decentralized computing platform. Its features include proof of stake consensus, formal verification (which lets developers verify the correctness of their code), and the ability to let stakeholders vote on changes to the protocol. Tezos's block creation process is called "baking" — Tezos holders who stake their tokens can receive Tezos tokens as a reward for creating and verifying blocks.

data.name: Ethereum Classic
data.description: Ethereum Classic is a cryptocurrency with a special focus on immutability, popularly expressed as “code is law.”

data.name: USD Coin
data.description: USD Coin (USDC) is a stablecoin fully backed by the US dollar and developed by the CENTRE consortium. Coinbase customers with US dollar accounts may exchange 1 USDC for US$1.00 (and vice versa) on Coinbase in jurisdictions where USDC support is available. The graph above reflects USDC’s current and historical redemption value of US$1.00, which may not match the price of USDC on other exchanges. USDC is an Ethereum token and is the only fiat-backed stablecoin currently supported by Coinbase.

data.name: Basic Attention Token
data.description: BAT is an Ethereum token that powers Brave Software's blockchain-based digital advertising platform. Internet users who browse the web using Brave's free web browser (available at Brave.com) can choose to replace the ads they see with ads on Brave's ad network. Users then receive BAT from advertisers as compensation for their attention.

data.name: Zcash
data.description: Zcash is a cryptocurrency that offers two types of addresses: transparent addresses that are publicly visible on the Zcash blockchain and shielded addresses that are more private. Coinbase customers can receive Zcash from both transparent and shielded addresses and send Zcash to transparent addresses. Sending to shielded addresses is not supported at this time.

data.name: 0x
data.description: ZRX is an Ethereum token that is used to power the 0x protocol. The protocol itself is designed to allow Ethereum tokens to be traded at a low cost directly from your wallet.

data.name: Augur
data.description: Augur’s Reputation token (REP) is an Ethereum token designed for reporting and disputing the outcome of events on online prediction markets. Reporters are rewarded for reporting the outcome of events correctly.

data.name: Dai
data.description: Dai (DAI) is a decentralized stablecoin running on Ethereum (ETH) that attempts to maintain a value of $1.00 USD. Unlike centralized stablecoins, Dai isn't backed by US dollars in a bank account. Instead, it’s backed by collateral on the Maker platform. Note: if the Dai credit system is upgraded or shutdown, Dai holders may need to convert their Dai to Ethereum through the Maker platform. Read more at makerdao.com/whitepaper.
